Starting Monday Claim-to-Citation Matrix
Version: 2026-05-20
Scope: Verified and/or peer-reviewed sources only

Scoring key
- Relevance: 1 to 5, where 5 means the source directly supports a core Starting Monday claim.
- Confidence: 1 to 5, where 5 means the source is clearly peer-reviewed or published by a highly reliable institutional publisher and is easy to verify.

How to read this matrix
- Best source = the single strongest source for the claim.
- Supporting sources = additional sources that reinforce the claim from adjacent angles.
- Use the most specific claim possible when writing product copy, articles, HBR material, or sales language.

1) Claim: Executive coaching works, but it works through specific mechanisms and context, not as a generic silver bullet.
Best source:
- Ely, Boyce, Nelson, Zaccaro, Hernez-Broome, and Whyman (2010). "Evaluating leadership coaching: A review and integrated framework." The Leadership Quarterly.
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.leaqua.2010.06.003
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
Supporting sources:
- Joo (2005). "Executive coaching: A conceptual framework from an integrative review of practice and research."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1177/1534484305280866
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
- Grover and Furnham (2016). "Coaching as a developmental intervention in organisations: A systematic review of its effectiveness and the mechanisms underlying it."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0159137
  Relevance: 4/5
  Confidence: 5/5
- Bozer and Jones (2018). "Understanding the factors that determine workplace coaching effectiveness: A systematic literature review."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1080/1359432X.2018.1446946
  Relevance: 4/5
  Confidence: 5/5
Use for:
- "Starting Monday is coaching infrastructure, not another coaching session."
- "The product improves the mechanism between sessions."

2) Claim: Executive coaching can improve individual outcomes, performance-related behavior, and multisource feedback.
Best source:
- Jones, Woods, and Guillaume (2016). "The effectiveness of workplace coaching: A meta-analysis of learning and performance outcomes from coaching."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1111/joop.12119
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
Supporting sources:
- Theeboom, Beersma, and van Vianen (2014). "Does coaching work? A meta-analysis on the effects of coaching on individual level outcomes in an organizational context."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1080/17439760.2013.837499
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
- Smither, London, Flautt, Vargas, and Kucine (2003). "Can working with an executive coach improve multisource feedback ratings over time? A quasi-experimental field study."
  Link: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1744-6570.2003.tb00142.x
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
- Nicolau et al. (2023). "The effects of executive coaching on behaviors, attitudes, and personal characteristics: a meta-analysis of randomized control trial studies."
  Link: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37333584/
  Relevance: 5/5
  Confidence: 5/5
Use for:
- "The product is aimed at measurable execution quality, not vibes."
- "Better preparation and follow-through should improve outcomes that coaches and executives care about."

3) Claim: The biggest coaching loss is not the session itself; it is what happens between sessions.
Best source:
