High-priority source stack for product messaging
If you need the shortest defensible stack, use these 10 sources first:
1. Kilburg (1996)
2. Ely et al. (2010)
3. Theeboom et al. (2014)
4. Jones et al. (2016)
5. Athanasopoulou and Dopson (2018)
6. Smither et al. (2003)
7. Gollwitzer (1999)
8. Bauer et al. (2007)
9. Ansoff (1975)
10. Kahneman and Klein (2009)

What this matrix supports in Starting Monday language
- "We support the work between the big moments."
- "The session is not the bottleneck; the between-session layer is."
- "Prep briefs convert intent into execution."
- "Signal tracking gives executives an early-warning system."
- "Readiness infrastructure beats generic coaching or generic job-board behavior."
- "The product improves coaching effectiveness without replacing human judgment."

Notes on limitations
- Books were intentionally excluded unless they had a clearly verified publisher page and direct relevance.
- A few institutional or review sources were included even where the exact full text was not easily fetched in-browser, because the DOI or PMID is stable and the publication venue is verified.
- This matrix is designed for claims support, not for exhaustive literature review.

Recommended next step
- Turn this into a feature-to-evidence table for the product page, investor deck, and HBR pitch.
